<div id="review_2916234334" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2916234334" />
    <a title="GTF" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/66513638-gtf"><img alt="GTF" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1594722618p2/66513638.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2916234334?book_show_action=true">Aug 16, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="GTF" class="user" itemprop="url" name="GTF" href="/user/show/66513638-gtf">GTF</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2916234334" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12457621643735642574">After reading &apos;Bad Science&apos; I don&apos;t think I will believe another health fad ever again. <br/><br/>Ben Goldacre&apos;s impressive aptitude for scientific analysis and research reveals how science is more complex than we realize, which unfortunately doesn&apos;t always satisfy our want for quick fixes to our health problems. Although complex in nature, Goldacre stresses that people are not incapable of understanding scientific facts or findings, it is often just a matter of people receiving false information through </span>
  <span id="freeText12457621643735642574" style="display:none">After reading 'Bad Science' I don't think I will believe another health fad ever again. <br /><br />Ben Goldacre's impressive aptitude for scientific analysis and research reveals how science is more complex than we realize, which unfortunately doesn't always satisfy our want for quick fixes to our health problems. Although complex in nature, Goldacre stresses that people are not incapable of understanding scientific facts or findings, it is often just a matter of people receiving false information through the media by people who believe they've discovered magical cures and remedies. Goldacre covers everything from the power of the placebo effect, mainstream medicine, homeopathy, nutritionists cherry picking the truth, and he even takes an unbiased stance on the pharmaceutical industry, and admits that while there are at times unethical tactics used by some people in the pharmaceutical industry, it does not mean that science and medicine are there to deceive people. Goldacre outlines that there are plenty of professionals in this field who care about the truth, and who are vying for the truth to receive recognition. <br /><br />It is both amusing and enlightening to read about Goldacre simply debunking a lot of mickey-mouse-science that we are surrounded by in the modern world, but there is a more serious side to this reality, including how some so-called scientists don't know how to correctly interpret research, and how a worrying amount of incorrectness is now being taught in nutrition courses at universities. The bottom line is Goldacre stressing that people should be aware of the potentially fatal consequences when the mainstream media ignores actual scientific findings for not being fun or marketable. <br /><br />This book would be a very informative and worthwhile read for anyone. My four-star rating is purely due to the fact that I prefer to read fiction, not because I can refute anything that Goldacre says.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12457621643735642574" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


