<span id="freeTextContainer13900788459342018938">Actual real proper medical doctor Ben Goldacre disassembles some of the biggest :cough: bullshitters supposedly sharing medical, health and/or nutrition theories or even cures at best just placebos, or at worse harmful, who in many cases have their voices amplified by the media. Although this book is really informative, interesting and at times funny, it also has an elitist edge to it, one that I can see Goldacre really tried not to give.<br/><img src='https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1597945129ra/29993639.gif' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/>He also was at pains not to make it like a text book, bit </span>
  <span id="freeText13900788459342018938" style="display:none">Actual real proper medical doctor Ben Goldacre disassembles some of the biggest :cough: bullshitters supposedly sharing medical, health and/or nutrition theories or even cures at best just placebos, or at worse harmful, who in many cases have their voices amplified by the media. Although this book is really informative, interesting and at times funny, it also has an elitist edge to it, one that I can see Goldacre really tried not to give.<br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1597945129ra/29993639.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>He also was at pains not to make it like a text book, bit it sure felt like it at times, and maybe this is the reason why false narratives do so well, because they are made to be easily assimilated; whereas the truth, like what Goldacre produces here cannot be so simply put, because reality is not simple. 7 out of 12.<br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1597945129i/29993640._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"></span>
